above-normal temperatures this winter, Grand Forks and East Grand Forks are moving less snow but sanding and salting a lot more. According to the National Weather Service in Grand Forks , temperatures in Grand Forks have been averaging almost seven degrees above normal since the beginning of October. The warmer temperatures mean more of a chance of mixed precipitation and potential for ice events, like the ice storm that hit at the end of December. Grand Forks also has seen less snow than last winter. Unlike last winter, which had seen almost 31 inches of snowfall by this time , Grand Forks has only seen 13 inches of snow since Oct. 1. “Compared to last winter, it’s a big change, because it seemed like we were always moving snow every day,” Grand Forks Public Works Operations Director Sharon Lipsch said. “This winter, we’re finding ourselves salting and sanding more because of the frost in the morning with the warmer temperatures.” Already this winter Grand Forks has sprayed more gallons of liquid anti-icing than it did all of last winter. Also, the city has used 2,050 cubic yards of sand so far this winter; in the last five years, the city has used an average of 2,230 cubic yards of sand for the entire winter. ADVERTISEMENT Even though the city is having to treat the roads for ice more, less snow generally means equipment repairs and fuel costs are down. The milder weather has also given public works staff time to complete other projects. “We’ve actually been fairly busy with other projects,” East Grand Forks Public Works Director Jason Stordahl said. “Cleaning and organizing the workshop, doing some remodels like painting rooms and we had more time for our Christmas tree pickup.” Warmer temperatures mean the weather is cloudier and foggier. It also increases the chances of mixed precipitation and the potential for freezing rain, drizzle and fog. The main culprit is the ongoing El Niño in the Pacific and the jetstream keeping much of the polar air well to the north. Grand Forks broke several daily records last month for warm temperatures. Already in February, Grand Forks has broken five daily records for the warmest daily recorded low temperatures. With roughly a month until the spring equinox, the darkest and traditionally coldest days of winter are past. The National Weather Service is predicting temperatures will remain above normal throughout February. ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT'}]

Please purchase a subscription to continue reading. Your current subscription does not provide access to this content. Welcome a Lifelong Friend - Open Your Home to a Foreign Exchange Student World Heritage International Student Exchange Program (WH), a Non-Profit, Public Benefit Organization, is seeking local families to host foreign exchange students this coming school year. World Heritage students come from a variety of countries worldwide: Italy, Denmark, Spain, France, Germany, Ukraine, Japan, Australia, to name just a few. They are between the ages of 15 and 18 years, and they are enthusiastic and excited to experience American culture, family life, school, sports. etc. They also love to share their own culture and language with their host families, who welcome the students into their home, not as a guest, but as a family member, giving everyone involved a rich cultural experience. Host families may be single parents, couples and single persons. The exchange students have pocket money for personal expenses and full health, accident and liability insurance. World Heritage students are carefully selected based upon academics and personality, and host families choose their student from different backgrounds, countries and personal interests. World Heritage also offers qualified American students the opportunity to learn another language and culture by spending a school year, semester or a summer with a host family in another country. If interested in hosting an exchange student or becoming an exchange student abroad, please call Debra at 1-800-888-9040, visit www.world-heritage.org or send an email to info@world-heritage.org to request more information or start the application process. Students are eager to learn about their American host family, so begin the process of welcoming your new son or daughter today. The memories and the relationship you create with your exchange student will stay with you forever. Contact: Debra Garbon, World Heritage Program Director, at 1-800-888-9040 or send an email to info@world-heritage.org Nice, Cozy 1 bedroom apartment. Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 7:43 pm Hillsboro Elementary School Principal Jon Dryburgh verbally accepted an offer to become the Hillsboro School District’s next superintendent on Wednesday night. Hillsboro Elementary School Principal Jon Dryburgh has accepted a verbal offer to replace Paula Suda as superintendent of Hillsboro Public Schools starting in July. The Hillsboro School Board wrapped up its third and final interview Wednesday with a trio of candidates who applied to become Hillsboro’s next superintendent. Following a 45-minute discussion about the merits of each finalist, board members voted to extend a contract offer to Dryburgh and ask him to take over as the school district’s top administrator. School Board President Tim Kozojed said Dryburgh, who has served as principal at Hillsboro Elementary School since 2013, demonstrated the leadership and focus that made him the board’s top choice to replace Suda, who plans to retire in June. “Jon understands the current state of the school and he’ll have the ability to put his leadership spin on things and figure out, with help from the board, where to take our school in the future,” Kozojed said. Kozojed praised Dryburgh for being a great communicator and someone whose life experiences would allow him to bring a wealth of knowledge to the position as a first-time superintendent. 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Dec. 29, 1944-Jan. 31, 2024 Minot Gary Lueck, the son of Harry and Ida (Roth) Lueck was born on December 29, 1944, in Minot, North Dakota. He died at the age of 79 years after a brief illness on January 31, 2024, at the Trinity Medical Center, Minot. Gary was raised in rural Denbigh in the home of his parents. He received his education at the White Rock Township School. After completing his education Gary worked with his dad on the family ranch. Gary and his parents later moved from the ranch into Towner where he worked at the Towner Nursery where Gary excelled in happiness. Gary knew everyone and they knew him by his warm smile and willingness to listen and talk with them and enjoy a game or two of cards together. He had many friends wherever he went and in 2012 when Gary moved into the Haaland Estates in Rugby he added to his many friendships. Gary was a faithful member of the Zion Lutheran Church in Towner and will be greatly missed by his many friends and relatives. He is survived by sister-in-law Lorna Lueck and numerous nieces, nephews, cousins and friends. He was preceded in death by his parents, Harry and Ida; sisters, Mary Kay Tonnesson; Wilma Wolfe; and Sandra Sandberg; brother, Gordie Lueck; brothers- in- law, Kenny Tonnesson; Francis Wolfe; and Sandford Berg. The family would like to thank the Haaland Estates for their 12 years of good care; the recent care at the Trinity Medical Center; and the care given by the Anderson Funeral Home. Funeral Services were held at 11:00 a.m. Wednesday, February 7th at Zion Lutheran Church in Towner with burial in the Granville Community Cemetery in Granville, ND. Mr. Wally Fretland, Officiating. Organist: Sharon St. Aubin Vocalist: Vernon Larson Casket Bearers: Larry, Lyle and Darin Lueck, Larry Sitter, Rob Kramer and Jerome Suchor Arrangements with the Anderson Funeral Home of Rugby and Towner Online registry: www.funeralsbyanderson.com Published by The Pierce County Tribune, February 10, 2024. Join thousands already receiving our daily newsletter. Copyright © The Pierce County Tribune | https://www.thepiercecountytribune.com | 219 South Main Ave., Rugby, ND 58368 | 701-857-1900'}]

The writing style and content are not particularly AI-like.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT KILLDEER — An advertisement from the cattle company Agridime included the phrase: “We know it sounds too good to be true.” Despite that, the company was still able to entice investors with the promise of returns of 15% to 20% — even as high as 32% — in the cattle market without having to do any of the work. The Securities and Exchange Commission took over the assets in December, and a complaint against the company said Agridime diverted tens of millions of dollars in investor funds to make Ponzi scheme payments to prior investors. The complaint says Agridime owes $191 million to investors in 15 states. About $40 million, or more than 20%, is owed to North Dakota investors, the North Dakota Securities Department said. So if it sounded too good to be true, how did so many investors get hooked? ADVERTISEMENT In North Dakota, it can be attributed in part to Agridime using a trusted cattle broker as a sales agent. Taylor Bang of Killdeer had worked with ranchers in North Dakota for years before getting involved with Agridime. “One hundred percent up and up,” Killdeer beef producer Tom Murphy said of his 20 years of doing business with Bang. Agridime was incorporated in Texas in 2017. Murphy said he was skeptical of Agridime at first, but neighbors who had invested said Agridime was holding up its end of the deal. Here was the deal: Invest $2,000 with Agridime, and in 12 months, get a 15% to 20% return. With a $100,000 investment, a 20% profit was guaranteed. Murphy got pulled in, and after his first contract paid off as promised, he reinvested. But his third contract is due to pay off in May. “That one isn’t looking so good,” he said. Murphy said he has benefited from North Dakota’s revitalized oil industry, giving him money to invest that would not have available before. He said other western North Dakota landowners are in the same situation. ADVERTISEMENT Murphy and North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner Doug Goehring both noted that cattle markets have been on the upswing, making the idea of larger-than-usual profit margins seem attainable. But Murphy admits that the Agridime profit margins seemed high. “There’s never been 30% profit margin in the history of the cattle market, ever,” he said. And then there was the Agridime business model. Agridime worked with feedlots in several states to bring cattle up to market weight but said it had its own meat packing plants in Kansas, Texas and Arizona. It also had its own distribution system and was marketing its meat as a premium product. By eliminating some of the steps in getting beef to market — cutting out the middleman — the company told Murphy it could achieve those profits. “They said they had their own packing facilities and were marketing directly over the internet,” Murphy said. “And they said that’s how come there was such a profit margin.” ADVERTISEMENT Farmers “do feel like the middleman is getting too much, and quite frankly, I get where that mentality comes from,” said Goehring, who is also a beef producer. “So it’s easy to get lulled into the ‘I’m getting screwed,’” way of thinking, Goehring said. Consolidation in the industry has left just four large meatpacking companies. Producers complain that the lack of competition hurts producers and benefits the packers. “The packers make as much money on that calf in 14 days as we do in a year,” Murphy said. Murphy said he still believes the Agridime model could have succeeded. “I don’t think it started off as a Ponzi scheme,” Murphy said. “I think it started off as a business they probably could have pulled off.” This story was originally published on NorthDakotaMonitor.com ______________________________________________________ This story was written by one of our partner news agencies. Please give us a call at 701-291-3455 Copyright © • Wick Communications Terms of Use | Privacy Policy WILLISTON — Thirty-nine projects, many involving mental health services, have been approved as part of the Williston Economic Development\'s Community Enhancement grant program. During the Williston City Commission\'s meeting on Jan. 23, the commission approved the Williston STAR Fund Advisory board\'s recommendations to award a total of $70,000 to the 39 projects. In all, a record number of applications — 53 in all — were received, asking for a total of $279,200. "One of the things we noticed this year was the number of projects geared to providing mental health services and we wanted these organizations to become established and sustainable so they can do some good in our community," said Mayor Howard Klug. The 39 organizations and projects which received the Community Enhancement grants are: Bethel Lutheran Foundation, $3,000; BIO Girls Williston, $2,500; Blast in the Badlands Gymnastics Meet, $1,000; ConnectUs Foundation, $5,000; Coyote Clay Target League, $2,000; Coyote Wrestling Club, $5,000; Crosby Country Club, $1,000; Davidson Park Tennis Court Enhancement, $3,000; Family Voices of North Dakota, $1,000; Feed My Starving Children-Watford Mobile Pack, $500; Fort Buford Sixth Infantry Regimental Association, $1,000; Good Samaritan Club, $5,000; HER Inspiration Resource Center Inc., $500; Highland Cemetery Association, $1,000; Korner Lions Club, $500; Marketplace for Kids, $1,000; McKenzie County Healthcare-Horizon Assisted Living, $1,000; McKenzie County Heritage Association, $2,000; MonDak Gymnastics Support Group, $1,000; Northern Lights Council-Boy Scouts of America, $1,0000; Northern Plains Youth of Christ, $1,000; Olive Motherhood Foundation, $3,000; Opportunity Foundation-2nd Annual Street Dance, $500; Ray Golf Association, $2,500; Savage Community Hall, $3,000; Square Your Actions, $1,000; Sunset Park District PreK Enhancement, $1,000; Teen & Miss Williston Local Competition, $1,000; The Bakken Classic Junior Livestock Show, $1,000; The Harmonic Williston Initiative/Harmonic Creative World, $500; The Stone Foundation (Milestone Health Partners), $5,000; The Stray Sanctuary, $1,000; Veterans and Friends of the Old Armory, $1,000; Watford City Park District, $1,000; Western Star Foundation-Brew Your Business, $3,500; Williston Band Boosters WHS/WMS, $500; Williston Basin Skating Club, $4,000; Williston Sea Lions-Training Camp, $500; and Williston Trinity Christian School, $1,000. Organizations and nonprofits who received CE grants are from the City of Williston, as well as surrounding areas, such as Ray, Watford City, and Crosby. "The Community Enhancement program is a way for the City of Williston to support quality of life projects throughout the region," said city administrator Shawn Wenko. "For the regional applicants that applied and were approved, it is our way of saying thank you for your support and for shopping in Williston and contributing to the STAR Fund." The Williston STAR fund is supported by a voter-approved one cent city sales tax, 75% of which supports infrastructure and debt reduction; the remaining 25% is used to support job creation and community development. The Securities and Exchange Commission took over the assets in December, and a complaint against the company said Agridime diverted tens of millions of dollars in investor funds to make Ponzi scheme payments to prior investors. The complaint says Agridime owes $191 million to investors in 15 states. About $40 million, or more than 20%, is owed to North Dakota investors, the North Dakota Securities Department said. So if it sounded too good to be true, how did so many investors get hooked? ADVERTISEMENT In North Dakota, it can be attributed in part to Agridime using a trusted cattle broker as a sales agent. Taylor Bang of Killdeer had worked with ranchers in North Dakota for years before getting involved with Agridime. “One hundred percent up and up,” Killdeer beef producer Tom Murphy said of his 20 years of doing business with Bang. Agridime was incorporated in Texas in 2017. Murphy said he was skeptical of Agridime at first, but neighbors who had invested said Agridime was holding up its end of the deal. Here was the deal: Invest $2,000 with Agridime, and in 12 months, get a 15% to 20% return. With a $100,000 investment, a 20% profit was guaranteed. Murphy got pulled in, and after his first contract paid off as promised, he reinvested. But his third contract is due to pay off in May. “That one isn’t looking so good,” he said. Murphy said he has benefited from North Dakota’s revitalized oil industry, giving him money to invest that would not have been available before. He said other western North Dakota landowners are in the same situation. ADVERTISEMENT Murphy and North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner Doug Goehring both noted that cattle markets have been on the upswing, making the idea of larger-than-usual profit margins seem attainable. But Murphy admits that the Agridime profit margins seemed high. “There’s never been 30% profit margin in the history of the cattle market, ever,” he said. And then there was the Agridime business model. Agridime worked with feedlots in several states to bring cattle up to market weight but said it had its own meat packing plants in Kansas, Texas and Arizona. It also had its own distribution system and was marketing its meat as a premium product. By eliminating some of the steps in getting beef to market — cutting out the middleman — the company told Murphy it could achieve those profits. “They said they had their own packing facilities and were marketing directly over the internet,” Murphy said. “And they said that’s how come there was such a profit margin.” ADVERTISEMENT Farmers “do feel like the middleman is getting too much, and quite frankly, I get where that mentality comes from,” said Goehring, who is also a beef producer. “So it’s easy to get lulled into the ‘I’m getting screwed,’” way of thinking, Goehring said. Consolidation in the industry has left just four large meatpacking companies. Producers complain that the lack of competition hurts producers and benefits the packers. “The packers make as much money on that calf in 14 days as we do in a year,” Murphy said. Murphy said he still believes the Agridime model could have succeeded. “I don’t think it started off as a Ponzi scheme,” Murphy said. “I think it started off as a business they probably could have pulled off.” This story was originally published on NorthDakotaMonitor.com ______________________________________________________ This story was written by one of our partner news agencies. The Hankinson Pirates (2-5) girls basketball team ran into the undefeated Sargent County Bulldogs (8-0) on Thursday, Jan. 4, at Hankinson High School. The Bulldogs cruised to a 79-25 victory. Layne Lovdokken, a high school senior in Hankinson, recently had the honor of being inducted into the National Technical Honor Society. BISMARCK, N.D. — The North Dakota League of Cities (NDLC) has awarded Rylee Steffens the 2024 Jan Jordan Scholarship for $1,000. This scholarship recognizes Steffens’ outstanding achievements and potential for leadership. The Lidgerwood Women’s Club sponsored the 97th Annual Honor Student Banquet, held Wednesday, May 1, 2024, at St. Boniface Church in Lidgerwood, North Dakota. 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': "ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT MOORHEAD — You always knew when Clyde Allen walked into a room. Not because he commanded attention — just the opposite. You almost sense he didn’t want to be the center of attention, despite an impressive career in state and local government and education. But it was hard not to notice him. He was tall, handsome and dignified. More importantly, he was kind, warm and genuine. It didn’t matter if he was speaking to a university president or the teenager at church bringing him a cup of coffee — everyone was important to Clyde. But no one was more important to Clyde Allen than the person he called “his best friend,” son Scott Allen. Recently, the two men died in the same room, 13 days apart. A nearly 60-year bond — built through father/son fishing trips, movie nights and just hanging out — will conclude with a joint funeral service on Friday, Feb. 16. Clyde was a native of Massachusetts who met the love of his life, Esther, in a dance class in Washington, D.C. Following their marriage, they moved to the Twin Cities, where they welcomed two children into the family. Daughter Cindy came first. She was nearly 5 years old when baby brother Scott was born. ADVERTISEMENT “He was always happy. He always had the biggest smile,” said Cindy Rogness, who now lives in Duluth. But Rogness said early in childhood they started noticing some issues with Scott. “There wasn’t really a set diagnosis. There were just so many things,” Rogness said. “In school, he had learning disabilities. He was hyperactive. And at that point, the autism spectrum really wasn’t much of a thing. I think looking back, he would have been deemed Asperger’s.” During this time, Clyde was making a name for himself in the Twin Cities both in the private and public sectors. He worked for Honeywell, the Minnesota Taxpayers Association and served on the Bloomington City Council. He eventually became the state commissioner of revenue under Gov. Al Quie. But Rogness said her parents also took the time to make sure Scott was involved and included, like any other kid. But after 25 years, a new opportunity arose in Moorhead. Clyde was hired at Concordia College to work as vice president of financial affairs and the business office. Former Concordia College president and friend Paul Dovre said Allen worked with “effectiveness and integrity” and he made everyone around him better. “He was an exemplar as a man of service, as a man of loyalty, as a man of great and good gifts which he’s shared so generously with his family and his community, with the college. Anything he committed to, he was all in,” Dovre said. ADVERTISEMENT Esther was also making a name for herself on campus and around town. Scott was also a frequent visitor to campus. “Scott was just a part of everything he (Clyde) did. He’d come to committee meetings and they’d go to sporting events,” Rogness said. “When a new movie came out that Scott wanted to see, they’d go to the midnight showing together because Scott wanted to go to the first show.” Dovre said he heard some of the best stories about Scott and Clyde’s time together when Clyde served on the prestigious University of Minnesota Board of Regents. “They referred to him sometimes as 'The 13th Regent,’ ” Dovre said with a laugh. “He would come to meetings waiting for his dad, but in the process, he got acquainted with the board members, with the president, and the vice president. He wasn't at all self-conscious about introducing himself to people that he didn’t know or people that were of high rank. He’d go to the occasional football game and be invited to sit in the president’s box.” In fact, Scott had the confidence to hobnob with North Dakota legislators. In 2005, he saw something that needed to be changed. Scott, who had a non-driver North Dakota photo identification, realized that, because of a glitch in the system, he could not have the “organ donor” designation on his card. According to his obituary, “Scott eventually got to testify in the North Dakota Senate and helped pass the legislation that changed that ruling. Scott received the very first non-driver photo ID card with a designation for being an ‘organ donor ’ following the change in ruling.” ADVERTISEMENT However, it wasn’t all serious business for the Allens. Forum columnist Jim Shaw said Clyde, Esther and Scott attended the Patriots’ Day gatherings he and Clyde cooked up a few years ago. Shaw said it was probably about 30 years ago when he and Clyde met and realized they had grown up just a few miles from each other in the suburbs of Boston. One thing led to another, and the two men discussed Patriots’ Day, a huge holiday in Massachusetts celebrated every year in April to honor some of the first battles of the Revolutionary War. “But we’re out here and it’s just another day and there’s nobody to celebrate or even talk about (it) with!” Shaw said. So the two men started calling each other every year on Patriots’ Day to mark it together. “He wouldn’t even say 'Hello.’ I would just pick up the phone and he’d say, 'Listen, my children and you shall hear of the midnight ride of Paul Revere on the 18th of April in 75’ and he would go on and on and he would read the whole poem and it was so cool,” Shaw said with a hearty laugh. The phone calls eventually turned into Patriots’ Day parties and, following Scott’s lead, Shaw and Clyde lobbied the North Dakota Legislature to make Patriots’ Day a holiday. ADVERTISEMENT “This Patriots’ Day just won’t be the same without him around anymore. I’ll just have an empty feeling without him,” Shaw said. “He was such a great guy. So warm and friendly. But that was our day and I’m going to miss him.” Life slowed down a bit for the Allens when Esther was diagnosed with Alzheimer’s disease in 2013. Clyde became her caregiver, until her death on Dec. 18, 2022. Both Clyde and Scott were surrounded by friends, but after 65 years of marriage, losing Esther was difficult. “He was a brave face, but he was lonesome for her. He always said to me, the hardest time was going to bed at night,” Rogness said. By this point, Scott was suffering from some physical ailments and was living at The Meadows on University, a skilled nursing facility. Scott and Clyde still talked on the phone a couple times a day, every day. Clyde’s health started to fail in his last few months, so the family started looking for a nursing home with hospice care. Right away, they thought about reuniting Scott and Clyde by moving Clyde into The Meadows. Scott’s roommate had just moved out, prompting Scott to suggest they share a room. “He was so excited to have Dad there with him,” Rogness said. ADVERTISEMENT That was on a Monday. By Tuesday, after spending the day together, her brother started to notice that his dad was different, Rogness said. “At that point, I think the reality started to sink in for Scott and he realized Dad’s going to die,” she said. That Tuesday afternoon, Scott’s oxygen levels started to drop and he was taken to the emergency room. The family knew he wouldn’t live long. They had the option of sending Scott to the hospital or bringing him back to the nursing home to be with his dad. The family decided that Scott would rather be with his dad, so they moved him back to the nursing home to be next to Clyde. “My dad couldn’t get out of bed. But the staff at The Meadows was absolutely wonderful. They rolled the bed right over next to dad’s and dad could reach over and hold his hand. For a couple of hours, my dad just got to hold his hand and laugh about memories,” Rogness said. “I really feel that Scott just decided he didn't want to live without his best friend. So he let go.” Scott Allen died the next day, Wednesday, Jan. 24, 2024, at the age of 59. Rogness said she asked her father, who was in hospice care, what he thought about having a combined funeral with Scott when he died. “My dad’s comment was, 'Oh, I wouldn’t want to take anything away from Scott’s service,’ ” Rogness recalled. “He was thinking about Scott and how he was going to be honored and not about himself.” Just 13 days later, Clyde Allen died on Tuesday, Feb. 6, 2024, at the age of 88. Rogness and the rest of the family started planning the joint service. ADVERTISEMENT Rogness has now lost all three members of her family of origin in just 14 months. She said her faith and friends are helping her see it through. She is also reflecting on the"}]

Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 7:43 pm A Bemidji, Minn., man has been charged with driving under the influence after his vehicle struck a Traill County Sheriff’s Department patrol vehicle Sunday night. Body Cota, 24, was driving a 2014 Hyundai Santa Fe in the southbound lane of Interstate 29 when his SUV struck an unoccupied 2022 Ford Explorer about 2 miles south of Buxton, according to the North Dakota Highway Patrol. The Highway Patrol reported that the Traill County patrol car was parked with its emergency lights activated to warn motorists of an emergency scene while authorities responded to a one-vehicle rollover in the area about 7:45 p.m. Sunday. Cota failed to take precautions as he neared the emergency scene and his vehicle struck the rear of the Ford Explorer, according to the Highway Patrol. Cota sustained minor injuries in the collision. No first responders were injured. Following the collision, Cota was charged with driving under the influence, unlawful possession of controlled substances and paraphernalia.
